{"parse":{"title":"Soldado de cuera","pageid":36635262,"revid":824838809,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:222px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Dragon_de_cuera.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d8/Dragon_de_cuera.jpg/220px-Dragon_de_cuera.jpg\" width=\"220\" height=\"191\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d8/Dragon_de_cuera.jpg/330px-Dragon_de_cuera.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d8/Dragon_de_cuera.jpg/440px-Dragon_de_cuera.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"1799\" data-file-height=\"1565\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Dragon_de_cuera.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div><i>Soldado de cuera</i><br /> <small>1: Leather jacket with seven layers<br /> 2: Saddle pommel and cantle<br />  3: <a href=\"/wiki/Carbine\" title=\"Carbine\">Carbine</a><br /> 4: <a href=\"/wiki/Saddle_bag\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Saddle bag\">Saddle bag</a><br /> 5: <a href=\"/wiki/Lance\" title=\"Lance\">Lance</a><br /> 6: <a href=\"/wiki/Pistol\" title=\"Pistol\">Pistols</a> hanging on each side of the fender<br /> 7: <a href=\"/wiki/Buckler\" title=\"Buckler\">Buckler</a><br /> 8: Boots and <a href=\"/wiki/Spur\" title=\"Spur\">spurs</a><br /> 9: Wooden <a href=\"/wiki/Stirrups\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Stirrups\">stirrups</a><br /> 10: <a href=\"/wiki/Cartridge_box\" title=\"Cartridge box\">Cartridge box</a></small> <sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup></div></div></div>\n<div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:222px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Possible_Navajo_charcol_cave_draving_of_soldado_de_cuera_cira_unknown.png\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/bd/Possible_Navajo_charcol_cave_draving_of_soldado_de_cuera_cira_unknown.png/220px-Possible_Navajo_charcol_cave_draving_of_soldado_de_cuera_cira_unknown.png\" width=\"220\" height=\"148\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/bd/Possible_Navajo_charcol_cave_draving_of_soldado_de_cuera_cira_unknown.png/330px-Possible_Navajo_charcol_cave_draving_of_soldado_de_cuera_cira_unknown.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/bd/Possible_Navajo_charcol_cave_draving_of_soldado_de_cuera_cira_unknown.png/440px-Possible_Navajo_charcol_cave_draving_of_soldado_de_cuera_cira_unknown.png 2x\" data-file-width=\"2642\" data-file-height=\"1782\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Possible_Navajo_charcol_cave_draving_of_soldado_de_cuera_cira_unknown.png\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>Possible Navajo charcoal cave drawing of soldado de cuera, date of drawing unknown</div></div></div>\n<p>The <b>soldado de cuera</b> (English, \"leather-jacket soldier\")<sup id=\"cite_ref-crespi_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-crespi-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>  served in the frontier garrisons of northern <a href=\"/wiki/New_Spain\" title=\"New Spain\">New Spain</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> They were mounted and were an exclusive corps in the Spanish Empire. They took their name from the multi-layered deer-skin cloak they wore as protection against Indian arrows. When New Spain's visitador (inspector general) Jos\u00e9 de G\u00e1lvez organized the <a href=\"/wiki/Portola_Expedition\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Portola Expedition\">Portola Expedition</a>, he was accompanied by a party of 25 soldiers, the \"finest horsemen in the world, and among these soldiers who best earn their bread from the august monarch whom they serve.\"<sup id=\"cite_ref-crespi_2-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-crespi-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> \n</p>\n<style data-mw-deduplicate=\"TemplateStyles:r856303468\">.mw-parser-output .templatequote{overflow:hidden;margin:1em 0;padding:0 40px}.mw-parser-output .templatequote .templatequotecite{line-height:1.5em;text-align:left;padding-left:1.6em;margin-top:0}</style><blockquote class=\"templatequote\"><p>The cuera, which gave them their name,  was a leather jacket, like a coat without sleeves,  proof against the Indians' arrows except at very  close range. For additional armor they had  shields and chaps. The shields, carried on the  left arm, were made of two plies of bull's hide,  and would turn either arrow or spear. The  leather chaps or aprons, fastened to the pommel  of the saddle, protected legs and thighs from  brush and cactus spines.<sup id=\"cite_ref-crespi_2-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-crespi-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p></blockquote>\n<p>They were armed with a short <a href=\"/wiki/Musket\" title=\"Musket\">musket</a>, a pair of pistols, a bow and arrows, a short sword, a lance, and a bull-hide shield (<a href=\"/wiki/Adarga\" title=\"Adarga\">adarga</a>). These frontier soldiers were recruited from among the <a href=\"/wiki/Mestizo\" title=\"Mestizo\">mestizo</a> population, Hispanicized Indians, and freed slaves. Most of the officers were <a href=\"/wiki/Criollo_peoples\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Criollo peoples\">Criollos</a>, whereas very few of the enlisted men had this distinction. The soldados de cuera manned the <a href=\"/wiki/Presidio\" title=\"Presidio\">presidios</a> that stretched from <a href=\"/wiki/Los_Adaes\" title=\"Los Adaes\">Los Adaes</a>, Louisiana, in the East, across Texas, New Mexico, and Arizona, to the Pacific Coast of <a href=\"/wiki/Alta_California\" title=\"Alta California\">Alta California</a> in the West.<sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Soldado_de_cuera&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<h3><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Notes\">Notes</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Soldado_de_cuera&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Notes\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h3>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Bueno, Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda (2014), <i>Las Guarniciones de los Presidios de Nueva Espa\u00f1a: Los Dragones Cuera</i>, Madrid: Ministerio de Defensa. p. 21.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-crespi-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-crespi_2-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-crespi_2-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-crespi_2-2\"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Cresp\u00ed, Juan, 1721-1782. <i><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/wayf?target=https%3A%2F%2Fbabel.hathitrust.org%2Fcgi%2Fpt%3Fid%3Duc1.%2524b233487%3Bpage%3Droot%3Bseq%3D9%3Bview%3D1up%3Bsize%3D100%3Borient%3D0\">Fray Juan Crespi: Missionary Explorer On the Pacific Coast, 1769-1774</a></i>. Berkeley, Calif.: University of California press, 1927.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-3\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://books.google.com/books?id=ewfAudJ_PX8C&amp;pg=PA426&amp;lpg=PA426&amp;dq=%22soldado+de+cuera%22+%22New+spain%22&amp;source=bl&amp